ed reform of state-level educational funding systems. Douglas Reed analyzes both the rhetoric of reform and the varying effects of these controversial decisions while critiquing the courts' failure to more clearly define educational equity. Well-written with keen insight throughout, the book concludes with an intriguing policy proposal that acknowledges obstacles to such efforts. This proposal aims to enhance education by fostering racial and economic integration locally. Setting the stage for a more coherent debate on this controversial issue and expanding our understanding of constitutional design, On Equal Terms will have far-reaching implications for law, public policy, politics, and not least, the future of American education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aDiscrimination in educationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aEducationxFinancexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aEducationzUnited StatesxFinance. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh  a.  aAbbott III decision.  aAllen, Yorke.  aBlack Power Movement.  aBonazzi, Robert.  aBrock, David.  aBurger, Warren.  aColeman Report (1966).  aConnecticut Supreme Court.  aCulberson, John.  aEvans, William N.  aFeinsod, Lawrence.  aFlorida Supreme Court.  aFoluke, Andaiye.  aGoodwin, Dorothy.  aGormley, William.  aGriffin, Stephen.  aHalpern, Stephen.  aHispanic students.  aHorton II decision.  aJackson, Kenneth.  aJohnson, Michael.  aKlagholz, Leo.  aLegal Defense Fund (NAACP).  aLieberman, Joe.  aMarshall, Thurgood.  aMcReynolds, James.  aMonetsano, Joseph.  aNeely, Richard.  aNew Jersey Supreme Court.  aOhio Constitution.  aOregon.  aPeters, Ellen.  aPoritz, Deborah.  aPyatt, Graham.  aRae, Douglas.  aRodriguez, Demetrio.  aRosenberg, Gerald.  aSchwab, R